'''Shikatsube no Magao''' (鹿津部 真顔, 1753 (Hōreki 3) – July 6, 1829 (Bunsei 12, 6th day of the 6th month)) was a late Edo period [[:en:Kyōka|kyōka poet]] and {{ill|gesaku writer|ja|戯作者|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/gesaku writer|qq=}}. His name is also written as 鹿都部真顔. He was commonly known as Kitagawa Kahei, with numerous pen names, including Ki Magao, Kyōkadō, Shakujō Sanjin, Haikai Utagaba, Manyōtei, Shihō Utakaki, Shihō Magao, Kōyaō, and Renagawa Kōchō, among others.<ref name=":0">{{Cite|和書|author=[[Masaru Okamoto]] and [[Sumio Kumo]]|title=Shinpan Kinsei Bungaku Kenkyū Jiten|date=2006-02|pages=275|publisher=Ōfū|ref=harv}}</ref>
== Biography == In 1781 (Tenmei 1), Shikatsube's name first appeared in the [[:en:Sharebon|sharebon]] *Sode Kagami* ("Sleeve Mirror"). During the Tenmei era, he published numerous works, including [[:en:Kibyōshi|kibyōshi]] and sharebon.<ref name=":0" /> In 1782 (Tenmei 2), he entered the world of kyōka poetry under the tutelage of {{ill|Motoki Ami|ja|高嵩松|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Motoki Ami|qq=}}. Around 1784 (Tenmei 4), he became a disciple of [[:en:Ōta Nanpo|Ōta Nanpo]] and formed the "Sukiya Ren" group alongside {{ill|Sangi Arimasa|ja|算木有政|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sangi Arimasa|qq=}}, {{ill|Zenya Kanerachi|ja|銭屋金埒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenya Kanerachi|qq=}}, and others.<ref name=":0" />
Eventually, he was counted among the "Four Heavenly Kings of Kyōka" alongside [[:en:Ishikawa Masamochi|Ishikawa Masamochi]] (Yadoya no Meshimori), {{ill|Kishi Bunshō|ja|岸文笑|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishi Bunshō|qq=}} (Atamimitsu), and Kanerachi.<ref name=":0" /> In 1794 (Kansei 6), Nanpo granted him the surname "Shihō," dividing the kyōka poetry world of the Kansei era with Yadoya no Meshimori.<ref name=":0" />
Magao aimed to correct what he saw as the unbridled and chaotic tendencies of Tenmei kyōka, advocating for {{ill|haikai uta|ja|俳諧歌|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/haikai uta|qq=}}, which he considered the original form of kyōka, rooted in Kamakura and Muromachi period traditions. However, this approach failed to gain public favor and ultimately contributed to the decline of kyōka.<ref name=":0" /> In his later years, he faced familial misfortune and poverty, dying in destitution.<ref name=":0" />
